Data Cleaning and Data Pre-processing¶

In [10]:
health_train_db.isnull().sum().sum()
Out[10]:
88
In [11]:
health_train2 = health_train_db.dropna()
health_train2.isnull().sum().sum()
Out[11]:
0
In [12]:
# Drop unnecessary column of the dataset
health_train2 = health_train2.drop('x14', axis=1)
In [13]:
# Convert Male and Female to binary Number
health_train2['x3'] = health_train2['x3'].map({'F': 1, 'M': 0})
health_train2["target"] = health_train2["target"].map({"Low risk": 3, "Moderate risk": 4, "High risk": 5})

Dataset Splitting into train and test format¶

In [15]:
# Split the dataset into features and target
X_value = health_train2.drop(["id", "target"], axis=1)
y_value = health_train2["target"]
In [16]:
# Splitting dataset on train/test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = split_process(X_value, y_value, test_size=0.3, random_state=0)

Save the Predicted label¶

In [35]:
# Create a new dataset for prediction results
pred_results = lds.DataFrame(columns=["id", "predicted_target"])
In [36]:
# Make predictions on each row of the original dataset
for index, row in health_train2.iterrows():
    id = row["id"]
    x_values = row.drop(["id", "target"])
    predicted_target = randomforestmodel.predict([x_values])[0]
    pred_results = pred_results.append({"id": id, "predicted_target": predicted_target}, ignore_index=True)
